  "prompt": "I can't remember the combination on my carlton suitcase, how do I 'crack' it?",
  "response": "If you\u2019ve forgotten the combination to your Carlton suitcase, here are some steps you can try to open it:\n\n### 1. **Check for a Default Combination**\n   - Many suitcases come with a default combination (e.g., 0-0-0 or 1-2-3). Try these common codes first.\n   - If the suitcase was reset to a default, it might still work.\n\n### 2. **Look for a Reset Button or Key**\n   - Some Carlton suitcases have a small reset button or a tiny hole near the combination lock. If you have the key or a thin tool (like a paperclip), you can reset the combination.\n\n### 3. **Search for the Original Combination**\n   - If you wrote down the combination somewhere (e.g., in your phone, email, or luggage tags), look for it.\n   - Check the suitcase\u2019s manual or packaging if you still have them.\n\n### 4. **Try a Brute Force Method**\n   - If you\u2019re willing to spend some time, you can try all possible combinations. Start at 0-0-0 and work your way up to 9-9-9. This method can take a while but often works.\n\n### 5. **Use a Flashlight to \u201cFeel\u201d the Lock**\n   - Shine a flashlight on the lock mechanism and slowly turn the dials. Look for gaps or notches in the wheels that align when the correct number is set.\n   - This method requires patience and a bit of trial and error.\n\n### 6. **Contact Carlton Customer Support**\n   - If you have proof of purchase or the suitcase\u2019s serial number, Carlton\u2019s customer service might be able to help you reset or recover the combination.\n\n### 7. **Take It to a Professional**\n   - If all else fails, a locksmith or luggage repair shop can usually open the suitcase without damaging it.\n\n### 8. **Avoid Force**\n   - Avoid forcing the lock open, as this could damage the suitcase. Use gentle methods first.\n\nLet me know if you need more detailed instructions!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
